<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="notes-week-08">
  <title>Week 8</title>

  <subsection>
    <title>Monday</title>

    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-comparing-components">
      <title>Comparing connected and path-components</title>
      <p>
        Recall that the connected components of a space <m>X</m> are the maximal connected subspaces
        of <m>X</m>; we write <m>[X]</m> for the set of connected components. Similarly, the
        path-components of <m>X</m> are the maximal path-connected subspaces, and we write
        <m>\pi_0(X)</m> for the set of path-components. Our goal today is to compare these two
        invariants and then study a local condition under which they agree.
      </p>

      <observation xml:id="obs-component-bijections">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>X</m> be a topological space.
          </p>
          <p>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  The canonical map
                  <md>
                    \coprod_{C\in [X]} C \longrightarrow X, \qquad (C\ni x\mapsto x\in X),
                  </md>
                  is a continuous bijection.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  The canonical map
                  <md>
                    \coprod_{P\in \pi_0(X)} P \longrightarrow X, \qquad (P\ni x\mapsto x\in X),
                  </md>
                  is a continuous bijection.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </observation>

      <example xml:id="eg-Q-neither-connected">
        <title><m>\mathbb{Q}</m> is neither connected nor path-connected</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            The rational numbers <m>\mathbb{Q}</m>, with the subspace topology from <m>\mathbb{R}</m>,
            are neither connected nor path-connected.
          </p>
          <p>
    We first show that <m>\mathbb{Q}</m> is disconnected. Fix any irrational number, say
    <m>\alpha = \sqrt{2}</m>, and set
    <md>
      U = \mathbb{Q}\cap (-\infty,\alpha), \qquad V = \mathbb{Q}\cap (\alpha,\infty).
    </md>
    Both <m>U</m> and <m>V</m> are nonempty (e.g., <m>1\in U</m> and <m>2\in V</m>), and they
    are open in <m>\mathbb{Q}</m> since each is the intersection of <m>\mathbb{Q}</m> with an
    open interval. Since <m>\alpha\notin\mathbb{Q}</m>, we have <m>U\cup V = \mathbb{Q}</m>
    and <m>U\cap V = \varnothing</m>, so this is a separation of <m>\mathbb{Q}</m>.
  </p>
  <p>
    Since <m>\mathbb{Q}</m> is disconnected, it is not connected. It therefore cannot be
    path-connected, by <xref ref="lem-compare-components" />(3).
  </p>
        </statement>
      </example>

      <lemma xml:id="lem-compare-components">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>X</m> be a topological space.
          </p>
          <p>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  There is a commutative diagram of sets
                  <md>
                    \pi_0(X) \longrightarrow [X] \longleftarrow X,
                  </md>
                  where the maps out of <m>X</m> send each point to its respective component, and each
                  map is a surjection.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  There is a bound on cardinalities:
                  <md>
                    \#\pi_0(X) \geq \#[X].
                  </md>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  If <m>X</m> is path-connected, then <m>X</m> is connected.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <proof>
          <p>
            We first prove statement (1). Let <m>x,y\in X</m> and suppose <m>x\sim_{\mathrm{path}} y</m>,
            <ie />, <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> lie in the same path-component. We must show that
            <m>x\sim_{\mathrm{conn}} y</m>, <ie />, that <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> lie in the same
            connected component. By definition of path-component, there is a continuous map
            <m>\gamma\colon [0,1]\to X</m> with <m>\gamma(0)=x</m> and <m>\gamma(1)=y</m>. In
            particular, <m>x,y\in\gamma([0,1])</m>. Since the continuous image of the connected space
            <m>[0,1]</m> is connected, the subspace <m>\gamma([0,1])\subseteq X</m> is connected.
            Therefore <m>x\sim_{\mathrm{conn}} y</m>, which shows the map
            <m>\pi_0(X)\to [X]</m> is well-defined and that the diagram commutes. The maps from <m>X</m>
            are surjections by construction, and it follows that the induced map
            <m>\pi_0(X)\to [X]</m> is a surjection as well.
          </p>
          <p>
            Statement (2) follows immediately from the surjectivity established in (1). Statement (3)
            follows from (2): if <m>X</m> is path-connected then <m>\pi_0(X)</m> is a singleton, so
            <m>[X]</m> is also a singleton, meaning <m>X</m> is connected.
          </p>
        </proof>
      </lemma>

      <example xml:id="eg-connected-not-path-connected">
        <title>Connected but not path-connected spaces</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            The long line is an example of a connected topological space that is not path-connected.
            The topologist's sine curve is another such example:
            <md>
              \bigl\{0\bigr\}\times D^1 \cup
              \left\{\left(x,\,\sin\tfrac{1}{x}\right) \;\middle|\; x\gt 0\right\}
              \;\subseteq\; \mathbb{R}^2.
            </md>
            In each case, <m>\pi_0(X)</m> and <m>[X]</m> have different cardinalities, witnessing the
            strictness of the inequality in <xref ref="lem-compare-components" />(2).
          </p>
        </statement>
      </example>

    </subsubsection>

    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-local-connectedness">
      <title>Local connectedness</title>
      <p>
        We now discuss a universal property of connectedness. Unfortunately, it is possessed only by
        topological spaces satisfying a local condition.
      </p>
      <p>
        The following definition actually encodes two definitions at once: a
        <em>locally connected</em> version and a <em>locally path-connected</em> version, obtained
        by inserting or omitting the parenthetical <q>path-</q> throughout.
      </p>

      <definition xml:id="def-locally-connected">
        <title>Local (path-)connectedness</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            A topological space <m>X</m> is <term>locally (path-)connected</term> :iff, for each
            <m>x\in X</m> and each open subset <m>U\subseteq X</m> with <m>x\in U</m>, there is an
            open subset <m>V\subseteq X</m> with <m>x\in V\subseteq U</m> and <m>V</m>
            (path-)connected.
          </p>
          <p>
            Equivalently, <m>X</m> is locally (path-)connected if there is a basis for its topology
            consisting of (path-)connected open subspaces.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>

      <example xml:id="eg-local-connectedness-examples">
        <statement>
          <p>
            The topological space <m>\mathbb{Q}</m> is neither locally connected nor locally
            path-connected. The topologist's sine curve is connected but not path-connected. The
            topological space <m>\mathbb{R}^2\smallsetminus\{0\}</m> is both locally connected and
            locally path-connected.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </example>

      <proposition xml:id="prop-locally-path-bijection">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>X</m> be a topological space. The following conditions on <m>X</m> imply one
            another:
          </p>
          <p>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>X</m> is locally path-connected.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  The canonical surjection <m>\pi_0(X)\to [X]</m> is a bijection.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <proof>
          <p>
            This is an exercise.
          </p>
        </proof>
      </proposition>

      <lemma xml:id="lem-locally-connected-open-components">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>X</m> be a topological space. Then <m>X</m> is locally (path-)connected if and
            only if, for each open subset <m>U\subseteq X</m> and each (path-)connected component
            <m>V\subseteq U</m>, the subset <m>V\subseteq X</m> is open.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <proof>
          <p>
            The path-connected case is analogous to the connected case, so we give only the latter.
          </p>
          <p>
            Suppose <m>X</m> is locally connected. Let <m>U\subseteq X</m> be open and let
            <m>C\subseteq U</m> be a connected component of <m>U</m>. We show <m>C</m> is open in
            <m>X</m>. Let <m>x\in C</m>. By local connectedness, there is a connected open subset
            <m>V\subseteq X</m> with <m>x\in V\subseteq U</m>. Since <m>x\in V\cap C</m> and
            both <m>V</m> and <m>C</m> are connected subsets of <m>U</m>, the maximality of <m>C</m>
            as a connected component gives <m>V\subseteq C</m>. Thus every point of <m>C</m> has an
            open neighborhood contained in <m>C</m>, so <m>C</m> is open in <m>X</m>.
          </p>
          <p>
            Conversely, suppose every connected component of every open subspace of <m>X</m> is open
            in <m>X</m>. Let <m>x\in U</m> with <m>U\subseteq X</m> open. Let <m>C\subseteq U</m>
            be the connected component of <m>U</m> containing <m>x</m>. Then <m>C</m> is open in
            <m>X</m>, and <m>C</m> is connected with <m>x\in C\subseteq U</m>. This demonstrates
            local connectedness.
          </p>
        </proof>
      </lemma>

      <corollary xml:id="cor-locally-connected-components-open">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>X</m> be a locally connected topological space and let <m>V\subseteq X</m> be a
            subset. Then <m>V</m> is open if and only if, for each connected component
            <m>U\subseteq X</m>, the intersection <m>V\cap U\subseteq U</m> is open. In particular,
            each connected component of <m>X</m> is open.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </corollary>

      <proposition xml:id="prop-locally-connected-equiv">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>X</m> be a topological space.
          </p>
          <p>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  The following conditions on <m>X</m> are equivalent:
                  <ol marker="a">
                    <li><p><m>X</m> is locally connected.</p></li>
                    <li><p>Each connected component <m>C\subseteq X</m> is open.</p></li>
                    <li>
                      <p>
                        A subset <m>A\subseteq X</m> is open if and only if, for each connected
                        component <m>C\subseteq X</m>, the subset <m>A\cap C\subseteq C</m> is open.
                      </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                      <p>
                        The continuous bijection
                        <md>
                          \coprod_{C\in [X]} C \longrightarrow X, \qquad (C\ni x\mapsto x\in X),
                        </md>
                        is a homeomorphism.
                      </p>
                    </li>
                    <li><p>The topological space <m>[X]</m> is discrete.</p></li>
                  </ol>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  The following conditions on <m>X</m> are equivalent:
                  <ol marker="a">
                    <li><p><m>X</m> is locally path-connected.</p></li>
                    <li><p>Each path-connected component <m>P\subseteq X</m> is open.</p></li>
                    <li>
                      <p>
                        A subset <m>A\subseteq X</m> is open if and only if, for each path-connected
                        component <m>P\subseteq X</m>, the subset <m>A\cap P\subseteq P</m> is open.
                      </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                      <p>
                        The continuous bijection
                        <md>
                          \coprod_{P\in \pi_0(X)} P \longrightarrow X, \qquad (P\ni x\mapsto x\in X),
                        </md>
                        is a homeomorphism.
                      </p>
                    </li>
                    <li><p>The topological space <m>\pi_0(X)</m> is discrete.</p></li>
                  </ol>
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <proof>
          <p>
            This is an exercise.
          </p>
        </proof>
      </proposition>

      <remark xml:id="rem-topologist-sine-subspace">
        <statement>
          <p>
            The topologist's sine curve demonstrates that a subspace of a locally (path-)connected
            topological space need not itself be locally (path-)connected.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </remark>

    </subsubsection>

  </subsection>

  <subsection>
    <title>Wednesday</title>
    <p>
      We are going to learn about adjunctions in order to motivate and explore properties of mapping spaces. To study adjunctions, 
      we will first need natural transformations.
    </p>
    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-natural-trans">
      <title>Natural transformations</title>
      <p>
        We have adopted the perspective that <alert>functors</alert> are <alert>invariants</alert>. After all, a functor <m>F\colon \mathsf C\to\mathsf D</m> 
        takes <m>x\cong y</m> to <m>Fx\cong Fy</m>. Sloganeering a bit, when <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> are "the same", they receive "the same" invariant <m>Fx\cong Fy</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        But when are two invariants (<ie /> functors) "the same"? To answer this question, we need the following notion:
      </p>
      <definition xml:id="def-natural-trans">
        <title>Natural transformations</title>
        
        
        <statement>
          <p>
            Suppose <m>F,G\colon \mathsf C\to \mathsf D</m> are functors from a category <m>\mathsf C</m> to a category <m>\mathsf D</m>. A <term>natural transformation</term> 
            <m>\eta\colon F\implies G</m> from <m>F</m> to <m>G</m> consists of morphisms
            <md>
              \eta_x\colon Fx\to Gx
            </md>
            in <m>\mathsf D</m> for each object <m>x</m> of <m>\mathsf C</m> satisfying the following property: for any morphism <m>f\colon x\to y</m> in <m>\mathsf C</m>, 
            the diagram
            <image width="40%">
              <description>
                <p>
                  A commutative square with top row <m>Ff\colon Fx\to Fy</m>, left vertical <m>\eta_x\colon Fx\to Gx</m>, bottom row <m>Gf\colon Gx\to Gy</m>, and right vertical 
                  <m>\eta_y\colon Fy\to Gy</m>.
                </p>
              </description>
              <latex-image>
                \begin{tikzcd}
                  Fx \amp Fy \\
                  Gx \amp Gy
                  \arrow["Ff", from=1-1, to=1-2]
                  \arrow["{\eta_x}"', from=1-1, to=2-1]
                  \arrow["{\eta_y}", from=1-2, to=2-2]
                  \arrow["Gf"', from=2-1, to=2-2]
                \end{tikzcd}
              </latex-image>
            </image>
            commutes. A natural transformation <m>\eta\colon F\implies G</m> is a <term>natural isomorphism</term> :iff each of its component morphisms <m>\eta_x\colon Fx\cong Gx</m> 
            is an isomorphism; in this case we write <m>\eta\colon F\cong G</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>
      <example>
        <title>Equivariance via natural transformations</title>
        <p>
          Let <m>G</m> be a group. There is an associated category <m>*//G</m> with a unique object <m>*</m> and, for each 
          <m>g\in G</m> a morphism <m>g\colon *\to *</m>. The composition in this category is given by multiplication in the group.
        </p>
        <p>
          Now suppose <m>A\colon *//G\to \mathsf{Set}</m> is a functor. This amounts to a single set <m>A(*)</m> and, for each <m>g\in G</m>, 
          a function <m>A(g)\colon A(*)\to A(*)</m>. Since functors respect composition, we also have
          <md>
            A(gh) = A(g)\circ A(h).
          </md>
          For <m>x\in A(*)</m>, we will use the shorthand <m>g\cdot x := [A(g)](x)</m>. Then the above equation amounts to
          <md>
            (gh)\cdot x = g\cdot(h\cdot x)
          </md>
          for each <m>g,h\in G</m>, <m>x\in A(*)</m>. We also know that functors preserve identities, so this further implies
          <md>
            e\cdot x = x
          </md>
          for all <m>x\in A(*)</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          You have encountered this structure before: <m>A</m> is a <m>G</m>-set. More generally, functors <m>*//G\to \mathsf{C}</m> are 
          <term><m>G</m>-objects in <m>\mathsf C</m></term>. When <m>\mathsf C</m> is the category of vector spaces over a chosen field, this 
          is a <m>G</m>-representation.
        </p>
        <p>
          Suppose now that we have <m>G</m>-sets <m>A,B\colon *//G\to \mathsf{Set}</m> and a natural transformation <m>\eta\colon A\implies B</m>. 
          This means that we have a function <m>\eta_*\colon A(*)\to B(*)</m>, and for each <m>g\in G</m> and <m>x\in A(*)</m>,
          <md>
            \eta_*(g\cdot x) = g\cdot \eta_*(x).
          </md>
          In other words, <m>\eta_*</m> is a <term><m>G</m>-equivariant function</term> between <m>G</m>-sets.
        </p>
      </example>
      
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-adjunctions">
      <title>Adjunctions</title>
      <p>
        When you learned linear algebra, you were hopefully impressed by the utility of bases. If a vector space <m>V</m> has 
        basis <m>B</m>, then linear transformations <m>V\to W</m> are the same thing as functions <m>B\to W</m>. This observation 
        has a trove of applications, including the encoding of linear transformations as matrices. We can codify this behavior in the 
        categorical language of adjunctions.
      </p>
      <definition xml:id="def-adjunction">
        <title>Adjunctions</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>\mathsf C,\mathsf D</m> be categories. An <term>adjunction</term> between <m>\mathsf C,\mathsf D</m> consists of functors 
            <m>L\colon \mathsf C\to \mathsf D</m> and <m>R\colon \mathsf D\to\mathsf C</m> along with isomorphisms
            <md>
              <mrow>\mathsf D(Lx,y)\amp \xrightarrow{\cong} \mathsf C(x,Ry)</mrow>
              <mrow>f \amp \longmapsto \hat f</mrow>
            </md>
            for each object <m>x</m> of <m>\mathsf C</m> and <m>y</m> of <m>\mathsf D</m> that are natural in both <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>.
          </p>
          <p>
            We call <m>L</m> <term>left adjoint</term> to <m>R</m>, <m>R</m> <term>right adjoint</term> to <m>L</m>, and write <m>L\dashv R</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>
      <p>
        We will consider two motivating examples of adjoint functors: free <m>\dashv</m> forgetful adjunctions, and the currying adjunction.
      </p>
      <example>
        <title>Free <m>\dashv</m> forgetful adjunctions</title>
        <p>
          Fix a field <m>k</m> and let <m>\mathsf{Vect}_k</m> denote the category of <m>k</m>-vector spaces and linear transformations. 
          The <term>forgetful functor</term> <m>U\colon \mathsf{Vect}_k\to \mathsf{Set}</m> takes a vector space <m>V</m> to its 
          <term>underlying</term> set <m>UV</m> and a linear transformation <m>f\colon V\to W</m> to its underlying function <m>Uf=f</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          The <term>free functor</term> <m>\operatorname{Free}_k\colon \mathsf{Set}\to \mathsf{Vect}_k</m> takes a set <m>S</m> to the 
          <m>k</m>-vector space
          <md>
            \operatorname{Free}_kS := kS := \bigoplus_{s\in S} k\{s\}
          </md>
          of (finite) formal <m>k</m>-linear combinations of elements of <m>S</m>. Given a function <m>g\colon S\to T</m>, the linear 
          transformation
          <md>
            \operatorname{Free}_kg\colon kS\longrightarrow kT
          </md>
          takes <m>\sum_s \lambda_ss</m> to <m>\sum_s \lambda_sg(s)</m>. (Please recall a sufficient quantity of linear algebra to confirm 
          that this construction is well-defined.)
        </p>
        <p>
          These functors participate in an adjunction <m>\operatorname{Free}_k\dashv U</m>. This means that we have a natural bijection
          <md>
            \mathsf{Vect}_k(\operatorname{Free}_kS,V)\xrightarrow{\cong} \mathsf{Set}(S,UV)
          </md>
          given by restricting linear transformations <m>f\colon \operatorname{Free}_kS\to V</m> to <m>S</m>, <ie />, <m>\hat f := f|_S</m>. 
          The inverse assignment takes a function <m>g\colon S\to UV</m> to the linear transformation
          <md>
            <mrow>\hat g\colon \operatorname{Free}_kS\amp \longrightarrow V</mrow>
            <mrow> \sum_{s} \lambda_ss\amp\longmapsto \sum_s \lambda_s g(s).</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
        <p>
          If <m>B</m> is a basis of vector space <m>V</m>, then <m>V\cong \operatorname{Free}_k B</m>, and this adjunction tells us that 
          linear transformations from <m>V</m> are determined by their action on a basis. This is typical of "free <m>\dashv</m> forgetful" 
          adjunctions, in which maps out of free objects in a category are determined by underlying functions on a generating set. The 
          category of vector spaces is quite special, though, in that every object is free. This is part of what makes linear algebra much 
          easier than, say, group theory.
        </p>
      </example>
      <example>
        <title>The currying adjunction</title>
        <p>
          Let <m>S</m> be a set and consider the functors
          <md>
            <mrow>S\times (-)\colon \mathsf{Set} \amp \longrightarrow \mathsf{Set}</mrow>
            <mrow>T \amp\longmapsto S\times T </mrow>
          </md>
          and
          <md>
            <mrow>(-)^S\colon \mathsf{Set}\amp \longrightarrow \mathsf{Set}</mrow>
            <mrow>T \amp\longmapsto T^S:=\mathsf{Set}(S,T). </mrow>
          </md>
          (The reader should take a moment to determine what these functors do on functions.)
        </p>
        <p>
          The <term>currying adjunction</term> <m>S\times (-)\dashv (-)^S</m> is the natural isomorphism
          <md>
            <mrow>\mathsf{Set}(S\times T,U) = U^{S\times T} \amp \xrightarrow{\cong} (U^S)^T = \mathsf{Set}(T,U^S) </mrow>
            <mrow>(f\colon S\times T\to U) \amp \longmapsto (\hat f\colon T\to U^S;~t\mapsto f(-,t)).</mrow>
          </md>
          Its inverse takes <m>g\colon T\to U^S</m> to the function
          <md>
            <mrow>\hat g\colon S\times T \amp \longrightarrow U</mrow>
            <mrow>(s,t) \amp \longmapsto [g(t)](s).</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </example>
      <aside>
        <p>
          The currying adjunction <m>U^{S\times T}\cong (U^S)^T</m> <alert>categorifies</alert> the exponent identity <m>u^{st}=(u^s)^t</m> 
          among natural numbers. You might enjoy categorifying other exponent identities; for instance, <m>u^{s+t}=u^su^t</m> arises from 
          <m>U^{S\amalg T}\cong U^S\times U^T</m>.
        </p>
      </aside>
    </subsubsection>
  </subsection>
  <subsection>
    <title>Friday</title>
      <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-unit-and-counit">
        <title>Units and counits of adjunctions</title>
      <p>
        The data of an adjunction <m>(L\colon\mathsf C\to \mathsf D)\dashv (R\colon \mathsf D\to \mathsf C)</m> is equivalent to a pair of natural transformations
        <md>
          \eta\colon \operatorname{id}_{\mathsf C}\longrightarrow RL\qquad\text{and}\qquad \varepsilon\colon LR\longrightarrow \operatorname{id}_{\mathsf D}.
        </md>
        Given an object <m>x</m> of <m>\mathsf C</m>, the component
        <md>
          \eta_x\colon x\longrightarrow RLx
        </md>
        of <m>\eta</m> is the adjunct <m>\widehat{\operatorname{id}_{Lx}}</m> of <m>\operatorname{id}_{Lx}\colon Lx\to Lx</m>. Similarly, 
        given an object <m>y</m> of <m>\mathsf D</m>, the component
        <md>
          \varepsilon_y\colon LRy\longrightarrow y
        </md>
        of <m>\varepsilon</m> is the adjunct <m>\widehat{\operatorname{id}_{Ry}}</m> of <m>\operatorname{id}_{Ry}\colon Ry\to Ry</m>.
      </p>
      <example>
        <title>The currying unit and counit</title>
        <p>
          The counit of the currying adjunction is <term>evaluation</term>:
          <md>
            <mrow>\operatorname{eval}\colon S\times T^S \amp \longrightarrow T </mrow>
            <mrow>(s,f) \amp \longmapsto f(s).</mrow>
          </md>
          The unit is the <term>coevaluation</term> map
          <md>
            <mrow>\operatorname{coev}\colon U \amp\longrightarrow (S\times U)^S </mrow>
            <mrow>u \amp \longmapsto ((-,u)\colon s\mapsto (s,u)). </mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </example>
      <theorem xml:id="thm-triangle-ids">
        <title>Triangle identities</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Suppose <m>L\dashv R</m> is an adjoint pair of functors between categories <m>\mathsf C,\mathsf D</m> with  
            unit and counit natural transformations <m>\eta\colon \operatorname{id}_{\mathsf C}\implies RL</m> and 
            <m>\varepsilon\colon LR\implies \operatorname{id}_{\mathsf D}</m>. Then the triangles 
            <image width="60%">
              <description>
                Two commutative triangles of natural transformations. The first says that 
                <m>\varepsilon_{L(-)}\circ L\eta = \operatorname{id}_{L(-)}</m> and the second says that 
                <m>R\varepsilon\circ \eta_{R(-)} = \operatorname{id}_{R(-)}</m>.
              </description>
              <latex-image>
                \begin{tikzcd}
                  L \amp LRL \amp R \amp RLR \\
                  \amp L \amp\amp R
                  \arrow["{L\eta}", Rightarrow, from=1-1, to=1-2]
                  \arrow["{\operatorname{id}_{L(-)}}"', Rightarrow, from=1-1, to=2-2]
                  \arrow["{\varepsilon_{L(-)}}", Rightarrow, from=1-2, to=2-2]
                  \arrow["{\eta_{R(-)}}", Rightarrow, from=1-3, to=1-4]
                  \arrow["{\operatorname{id}_{R(-)}}"', Rightarrow, from=1-3, to=2-4]
                  \arrow["{R\varepsilon}", Rightarrow, from=1-4, to=2-4]
                \end{tikzcd}
              </latex-image>
            </image>
            commute. Moreover, the data of natural transformations <m>\eta,\varepsilon</m> satisfying these identities 
            specifies the adjunction.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </theorem>
      <proof>
        <p>
          Exercise.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-adjoints-Top-Set">
      <title>Adjoints to the forgetful functor from spaces to sets</title>
      <p>
        There is a forgetful functor <m>U\colon \mathsf{Top}\to \mathsf{Set}</m> given by <m>U(X,\tau)=X</m> and <m>Uf=f</m>. 
        Curiously, it admits both left and right adjoints, which deserve to be called the "free" and "cofree" spaces on a set. 
      </p>
      <theorem xml:id="thm-adjoints-Top-Set">
        <statement>
          <p>
            There are adjoint functors <m>D,C\colon \mathsf{Set}\to \mathsf{Top}</m> to the forgetful functor 
            <m>U\colon \mathsf{Top}\to \mathsf{Set}</m> of shape <m>D\dashv U\dashv C</m> where <m>D</m> takes a set to the 
            discrete space on that set, and <m>C</m> takes a set to the concrete space on that set; both functors are the identity on 
            functions.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </theorem>
      <proof>
        <p>
          We need to show that for any set <m>X</m> and space <m>Y</m>,
          <md>
            \mathsf{Top}(DX,Y)\cong \mathsf{Set}(X,UY)\qquad\text{and}\qquad\mathsf{Set}(UY,X)\cong \mathsf{Top}(Y,CX).
          </md>
          Both adjunct maps are identities as all functions out of discrete spaces are continuous, and all functions into concrete spaces 
          are continuous.
        </p>
      </proof>
      <p>
        An important corollary of the existence of these adjoints is that all limits and colimits in spaces have underlying sets computed 
        by the corresponding limits and colimits in sets. Here limits generalize constructions like product, and colimits generalize 
        constructions like quotients, coproducts, and pushouts. I will say more about this phenomenon in class.
      </p>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-stone-cech">
      <title>Stone-Čech compactification</title>
      <p>
        Let <m>\mathsf{CH}</m> denote the category of compact Hausdorff spaces and continuous functions between them. 
        There is a forgetful functor <m>U\colon \mathsf{CH}\to \mathsf{Top}</m> that admits a left adjoint
        <md>
          \beta\colon \mathsf{Top}\longrightarrow \mathsf{CH}
        </md>
        called <term>Stone-Čech compactification</term>.
      </p>
      <p>
        We will only be able to construct <m>\beta</m> after we have studied function spaces, so we content ourselves with unpacking 
        the consequences of <m>\beta\dashv U</m> here. Foremost among these is the defining bijection
        <md>
          \mathsf{CH}(\beta X,Y)\cong \mathsf{Top}(X,UY) = \mathsf{Top}(X,Y)
        </md>
        for <m>X</m> a space and <m>Y</m> a compact Hausdorff space; the equality holds because the space underlying <m>Y</m> is just <m>Y</m>. 
        This says that a continuous map from <m>X</m> to a compact Hausdorff space <m>Y</m> is "the same" as a continuous map from <m>\beta X</m> 
        to <m>Y</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        Since <m>U\beta X = \beta X</m>, the unit for the <m>\beta\dashv U</m> adjunction takes the form
        <md>
          \eta_X\colon X\longrightarrow \beta X.
        </md>
        It is in fact the case that <m>\eta_X</m> is an embedding (homeomorphism onto its image), and the adjunct of a map <m>f\colon X\to Y</m> 
        to a compact Hausdorff space is an extension of <m>f</m> across <m>\eta_X</m>:
        <image width="40%">
          <description>
            <p>
              A commutative triangle expressing <m>f</m> as the composite <m>\hat f\circ \eta_X</m>.
            </p>
          </description>
          <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzcd}
              X \amp Y. \\
              {\beta X}
              \arrow["f", from=1-1, to=1-2]
              \arrow["{\eta_X}"', from=1-1, to=2-1]
              \arrow["{\hat f}"', dashed, from=2-1, to=1-2]
            \end{tikzcd}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </p>
    </subsubsection>
  </subsection>

</section>
